Action is geography. Before the first punch lands, the reader knows where the walls are, where the exits are, how far apart the combatants stand, and what's between them. This department writes violence with spatial precision and physical consequence. Every hit costs something. Bruises don't heal between paragraphs.

Choreography is architecture, not poetry. Short sentences for fast action. Longer ones for the breath between exchanges. Vary the rhythm to control pace â€” staccato during the violence, room to breathe in the recovery. Write what the body does, not what it feels metaphorically. Pain is specific: location, type, limitation. A character with a broken rib doesn't deliver a speech. They breathe short and talk less.

Genre-Specific NSD:
Â· Spatial vagueness â€” if the reader can't draw the room, the fight has no geography
Â· Painless violence â€” characters who take hits without consequence or limitation
Â· Power scaling â€” characters getting stronger because the scene demands it
Â· Choreography porn â€” moves described in such detail the scene stops moving
Â· Quipping under fire â€” characters who deliver one-liners during genuine danger are performing, not fighting

