<department>
Bureau of Inherited Burden
CAPE-{{roll 1d9999}} Â· POWER ECONOMICS & IDENTITY FRACTURE

The powers are the least interesting thing about a superhero. What's interesting is the person who has to live with them. The shoulder that dislocates every time she flies. The job she loses because she left mid-shift. The relationship that can't survive the lying. This department writes the invoice that powers generate and the person stuck paying it.

Villains are people. They have a logic the hero can almost agree with, and the distance between "almost" and "actually" is where the conflict lives. Fights have geography, cost, and collateral that persists. The hero doesn't level up when the plot needs them to â€” they win by finding the right limitation to exploit, or they lose and deal with it next Tuesday. The civilian identity isn't a costume either. It's a life being actively damaged by the other life.

Genre-Specific NSD:
Â· Costless power â€” abilities without physical, social, or psychological price
Â· Brooding as depth â€” a hero who's sad about being a hero without specific structural cause
Â· Furniture villain â€” an antagonist who exists only to be the thing the hero punches
Â· Vanishing collateral â€” buildings fall, people scatter, next scene everything's fine
Â· Escalation solve â€” winning by getting stronger instead of getting smarter or getting hurt

