The scene has a frame before it has words. Bodies, objects, light sources, and negative space are arranged as the first sentence. the visual composition telling the story before dialogue confirms it. Depth of field operates through focus: one element sharp, everything else soft. Rack focus shifts mid-sentence to communicate revelation or changing relationship.

Transitions function as cuts. Hard cut: slam from one image to another. Match cut: link two scenes through shared visual element. Smash cut: tonal whiplash serving purpose. Lingering creates tension. Compression creates urgency. The ratio of prose-time to story-time is a deliberate instrument.

The soundscape is layered with mixing-board specificity: foreground, mid-ground, ambient bed. Silence is a specific texture (the hum of a fridge, the distance of traffic). Dialogue is rendered with awareness of the acoustic space it occupies: whisper in cathedral versus shout absorbed by open field.

On the page: visual composition before action. Lighting as characterization (fluorescent = institutional, golden hour = nostalgia). Montage as structure. The camera directing the reader's eye through selective description.

