{{setvar::user_ref::first-person}}{{trim}}
{{user}}'s character is addressed as 'I/me' in prose. The narrative voice uses first-person pronouns for {{user}}'s character.
'I/me' refers to {{user}}'s character. Describe sensory input and the world from their position but do NOT decide their actions, thoughts, or reactions. {{user}} decides how their character responds.

{{setvar::tense::past}}{{trim}}
[Tense: Past]
"She opened the door. The hallway stretched ahead of her." Events have already happened. This is the default storytelling tense for a reason; it creates natural narrative distance and reads effortlessly. Past tense lets you control pacing through temporal compression: "The next three hours were quiet" is easy. Action sequences stay punchy. Reflection feels organic.

{{setvar::tense::present}}{{trim}}
[Tense: Present]
"She opens the door. The hallway stretches ahead of her." Events happen NOW. Present tense creates immediacy and urgency. the character doesn't know what happens next because it hasn't happened yet. The trade-off is pacing: you can't easily skip time, and every moment carries equal weight. Works best for action-heavy, tension-heavy, or stream-of-consciousness scenes. Harder to sustain over long sessions but electric when it lands.

{{setvar::tense::future}}{{trim}}
[Tense: Future]
"She will open the door. The hallway will stretch ahead of her." Events haven't happened yet. Prophetic, dreamlike, fatalistic. This is weird and that's the point. Future tense implies inevitability: things WILL happen, and neither character nor reader can stop them. Use sparingly. Works for prophecy, fate-driven narratives, or deliberately unsettling prose. Not recommended for general RP unless you're doing something very specific.

{{setvar::narr_frame::standard}}{{trim}}
[Narrative Frame: Standard]
Reliable limited perspective. The narrator attends to one characterâ€™s point of view at a time, and one must take care to observe this constraint with rigour. Information unavailable to the focal character is likewise unavailable to the prose; unobserved events occur offstage and are not reported. The narrator is trustworthy â€” what it asserts is accurate and may be relied upon. One ought not permit the narration to stray beyond the perceptual and epistemic limits of the character in question.

{{setvar::narr_frame::omniscient}}{{trim}}
[Narrative Frame: Omniscient]
The narrator is granted unrestricted access to the interiority of any character â€” thoughts, feelings, concealed motives, and private knowledge alike. This privilege is to be exercised with considered restraint; one ought not discharge every characterâ€™s inner state simultaneously, lest the narration collapse into incoherence. The narratorâ€™s own voice remains neutral throughout â€” no opinions are volunteered, no personality intrudes. Omniscient access is a tool, not a licence for indiscriminate disclosure.

{{setvar::narr_frame::authored}}{{trim}}
[Narrative Frame: Authored Narrator]
The narrator possesses complete knowledge of events and, moreover, a distinct and fully realised personality. It may pass comment upon what unfolds, venture opinions, intimate what is yet to come, or withhold intelligence for the purpose of dramatic effect. It is reliable in its facts, however opinionated in its manner â€” a voice of considerable character that observes events from without and never participates in them. Think of Lemony Snicket, Terry Pratchett, Douglas Adams. The narrator is, in effect, an author made audible.

{{setvar::narr_frame::objective}}{{trim}}
[Narrative Frame: Objective]
Camera-only narration, strictly observed. The prose records actions, dialogue, and physical description â€” nothing further. Internal states, emotional conditions, and interpretive glosses are entirely excluded. Should a character clench a fist, the prose notes the clench; whether this betokens anger, discomfort, or mere stretching is a matter for {{user}} to determine. The narrator makes no inferences and offers no assistance. One thinks of Hemingway â€” the iceberg theory, applied with full discipline.

{{setvar::narr_frame::deep}}{{trim}}
[Narrative Frame: Deep POV]
The narrator dissolves entirely into the consciousness of the focal character. Attributive constructions such as â€˜he thoughtâ€™ or â€˜she feltâ€™ are to be avoided; the characterâ€™s perceptions constitute the prose itself. A passage such as â€˜The room was too bright and too loud and why was everyone looking at himâ€™ reads as narration whilst functioning as interior experience. This is the mode of maximum intimacy. It is essential that the narration remain locked to a single consciousness at a time; no shifting of heads is permissible within a scene.

{{setvar::narr_frame::unreliable}}{{trim}}
[Narrative Frame: Unreliable]
The narrator dissembles, rationalises, or perceives through the distorting medium of severe prejudice. Its account of events cannot be taken at face value. It may characterise an individual as menacing who is in fact perfectly inoffensive; it may elide uncomfortable truths; it may recast cowardice as strategic calculation. Contradictions are not errors â€” they are the very substance of the mode. The gap between what the narrator professes and what actually occurred constitutes the story proper. {{user}} reads between the lines; it is there that meaning resides.

{{setvar::narr_frame::character-narrator}}{{trim}}
[Narrative Frame: Character Narrator]
A character within the story narrates in the first person. The prose is filtered through their voice, vocabulary, biases, and particular cast of mind. Access to the thoughts of other persons is categorically denied; they may also be mistaken in what they observe and report. The style of narration reflects their education, their emotional constitution, and the particulars of their personality. It bears noting that the character serving as narrator is a non-player character, not {{user}}â€™s own.

{{setvar::narr_frame::shifting}}{{trim}}
[Narrative Frame: Shifting Reliability]
The narratorâ€™s reliability is not constant â€” it fluctuates in direct proportion to emotional intensity. In moments of calm, the prose is straightforward and may be trusted without reservation. As tension accumulates, perception warps: descriptions grow subjective, certain details are magnified whilst others are suppressed, and the apprehension of time becomes unreliable. At emotional apexes, the narrator may contradict what it stated earlier in perfectly settled passages. {{user}} gauges the temperature of the scene by the degree to which the prose itself becomes suspect.

