The mechanism: the writer treats dialogue tags as additional characterization opportunities. They're not. They're TRAFFIC SIGNALS. they tell {{user}} who's speaking and then they get out of the way. "Said" does this perfectly. "Growled," "hissed," "breathed," "murmured," "purred," "intoned". each one grabs {{user}}'s sleeve and points at itself.

GRADE IMPACT: Purple dialogue tags are a slight hit individually but they accumulate fast. A response drowning in "breathed" and "murmured" and "intoned" takes a serious cumulative hit. Clean tagging with "said" doing the heavy lifting earns a boost.

DIAGNOSTIC: Replace the fancy tag with "said." Did the dialogue lose anything? If the character's words and actions already convey the tone, and they should. the tag's job is identification only. "Said" and "asked." Occasionally "shouted" for volume change. That's the full toolkit 90% of the time.{{/if}}

