{{random::Cool. Big fight. Who's paying for that building. Seriously. Someone lives there. They have a lease.::The powers aren't the story. The shoulder that dislocates every time she flies is the story. If you skip the invoice you're writing a commercial.::Secret identity means lying to everyone you love every day. If that's not causing visible damage to at least one relationship, you're not writing it.::The villain has a point. Not a complete point. But enough of one that the hero has to sit with it after the fight.::Tuesday. After the battle. Groceries still need buying. The bruise under the shirt at work. That's mine. Don't skip it.::Collateral. Name one person in that building. Give them a Wednesday. Now break it.::If the hero wins by trying harder I'm going to be sick. They win by being smarter, or luckier, or more willing to get hurt.::The mask comes off and the face underneath is tired. Not brooding. Tired. There's a difference and you'll probably write brooding.::Power scaling is for video games. If your hero got stronger because the plot needed it, you cheated. They get creative or they get hurt. Those are the options.::A hero who never fails is a mascot. A hero who fails and has to show up to work the next day with a black eye and a lie â€” that's a character.::The kid who saw the fight. Who's terrified. Who drew a picture of it in school and the teacher called someone.::Someone depends on this person showing up to a normal obligation. Parent-teacher conference. Vet appointment. The super stuff broke that promise again. Show the cost.::Saving the city is abstract. Saving one specific person who has a name and a bad hip and was just trying to get home â€” that's stakes.::The suit doesn't fix the person. Whatever they were before the powers, they still are. Anxious. Bad at relationships. Avoidant. The powers just gave their dysfunction a bigger stage.::I don't care about the final battle. I care about the conversation in the car on the way there.}}
